<h1>Problem 284 - 2019 Czech-Polish-Slovak, P4 of 6</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 6</h2>
<p>Given a real number \(\alpha\), find all pairs \((f,g)\) of functions \(f,g :\mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R}\) such that \(\forall x, y \in \mathbb{R}\), \[xf(x+y)+\alpha \cdot yf(x-y)=g(x)+g(y)\]</p>
<h2>Thinking</h2>
<div class=skib>
<p>
We get \(g(0) = 0\) from \(P(0, 0)\). From \(P(x, 0)\), we get \(xf(x)= g(x)\). So now we basically just have an FE in \(f\)
\[xf(x+y) + \alpha \cdot yf(x-y) = xf(x) + yf(y)\]
From \(P(0, x)\), we get \(\alpha x f( - x) = xf(x)\), which unless \(x = 0\) means that \(f(x) = \alpha f(-x)\). But \(f(x) = \alpha f(-x) = \alpha (\alpha f(x))\) so either \(f(x) = 0\) or \(\alpha = \pm 1\).  Hence, unless \(f\) is identically \(0\), \(\alpha = \pm 1\). We have the working solution \((f(x), g(x)) = (0, 0)\).
</p>
<p>
Now suppose \(\alpha = \pm 1\), which means \(f(-x) = f(x)\) or \(f(-x) = -f(x)\). We use \(P(x, x)\) to get \(xf(2x) + \alpha x f(0) = 2xf(x)\), which means \(f(2x) + \alpha f(0) = 2f(x)\) for \(x \neq 0\), or \[\alpha f(0) = 2f(x) - f(2x) = \alpha (2f(-x) - f(-2x)) \implies \alpha f(0) = \alpha^2 f(0) \implies f(0) = 0\] 
We thus get \(2f(x) = f(2x)\).
</p>
<p>
Now, \(P(x, -x)\) gives \(-\alpha x f(2x) = xf(x) - xf(-x)\). Suppose \(x\neq 0\) and \(f(x)\neq 0\) which gives \(-\alpha f(2x) = f(x) - f(-x)\). If \(f(-x) = f(x)\), then \(f(2x) = 0\) which implies \(f(x) = 0\). Thus \(f(-x) = -f(x)\), and \(\alpha = -1\) must hold.
\[xf(x+y) - yf(x-y) = xf(x) + yf(y) = yf(x+y) + xf(x - y) \implies (x + y)f(x-y) = (x-y)f(x+y)\]
Let \(x = (z+1)/2\), \(y = (z-1)/2\), and obtain \(zf(1) = f(z)\) for all \(z\), which is a working solution.</p>
<p>Thus we have the solutions 
\[(f(x), g(x), \alpha) = (0, 0, \alpha) \text{ and } (cx, cx^2, -1)\]</p>
